Let's start by calculating $\phi$ and $\phi'$. This is a simple quadratic trinomial:

$$
\phi=\frac{1+\sqrt{5}}{2} \quad \phi'=\frac{1-\sqrt{5}}{2}
$$

It is easy to verify that the formula works for $F_{1}$. For $F_{2}$, we will use the relations $\phi^{2}=\phi+1$ (the same for $\phi'$):

$$
\frac{\phi^{2}-\phi'^{2}}{\sqrt{5}}=\frac{(\phi+1)-(\phi'+1)}{\sqrt{5}}=1=F_{2}
$$

Now let's consider the induction: suppose the formula is true for $F_{n}$ and $F_{n+1}$. We will use the following formula:

$$
\begin{gathered}
\phi^{n+1}+\phi^{n}=\phi^{n}(\phi+1)=\phi^{n} \cdot \phi^{2}=\phi^{n+2} \\
F_{n+2}=F_{n+1}+F_{n}=\frac{\phi^{n+1}-\phi'^{n+1}+\phi^{n}-\phi'^{n}}{\sqrt{5}}=\frac{\phi^{n+2}-\phi'^{n+2}}{\sqrt{5}}
\end{gathered}
$$

which completes the induction.

